COMP47670 Assignment II Autumn 2023¶

Time Series Running Data¶

Objective¶

The objective of this assignment is to identify good models for classifying time series data.
The data is from an accelerometer sensor and there are samples of fatigued and non-fatigued running. The data has been segmented into strides and the segments (samples) are labelled F (fatigued) and NF (not fatigued). The data for two subjects A and B are available in the files fatigueA.csv and fatigueB.csv. This dataset is extracted from a much larger dataset described here.
At present, the best performing method for time-series classification is Rocket. A rocket implementation is available in the sktime tool kit. This sktime implementation can be used in this assignment.
Some code to get you started in available in the notebook RunningCore.

# Resetting the lists for storing cross-validation accuracies
cv_accuracies = []

# Custom loop to perform cross-validation for a range of iterations
for iter in range(1, 1001, 50):  # Testing in steps of 50 iterations
    model_cv = SGDClassifier(loss='log_loss', max_iter=iter, tol=None, random_state=10)
    model_cv_pipeline = make_pipeline(StandardScaler(), model_cv)

    # Performing 5-fold cross-validation to evaluate the model
    cv_scores = cross_val_score(model_cv_pipeline, X, y, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')

    # Calculating and storing the average cross-validation accuracy
    cv_accuracy = np.mean(cv_scores)
    cv_accuracies.append(cv_accuracy)

# Plotting the accuracy over iterations
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(range(1, 1001, 50), cv_accuracies, label='Cross-validation Accuracy', marker='o')
plt.xlabel('Iterations')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.title('Cross-validation Accuracy Over Iterations')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

  • The accuracy increases as the number of iterations increases at the peak of iterators = 100.

  • After a certain number of iterations, the losses start to plateau, indicating that additional iterations are not leading to significant improvements in model performance.

  • Should select a max_iter value where the testing loss stabilize, I select 100 for 'max_iter'.

from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.preprocessing import RobustScaler, MinMaxScaler

tscv = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits=5)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=10)

# Create a pipeline template for classification
pipeline_template = Pipeline([
    ('scaler', StandardScaler()),  # Placeholder scaler
    ('classifier', KNeighborsClassifier())  # Placeholder classifier
])

# Parameter grid for K-Nearest Neighbors Classifier
param_grid_knn = {
    'scaler': [StandardScaler(), RobustScaler(), MinMaxScaler()],
    'classifier__n_neighbors': [3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 15],
    'classifier__weights': ['uniform', 'distance']
}

# Grid search setup for KNN Classifier
grid_search_knn = GridSearchCV(pipeline_template, param_grid_knn, cv=tscv, scoring='accuracy', verbose=1)
grid_search_knn.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Best parameters and accuracy for KNN Classifier
best_params_knn = grid_search_knn.best_params_
best_accuracy_knn = grid_search_knn.best_score_

best_params_knn, best_accuracy_knn

In [21]:
n_neighbors_range = range(1, 10)  # Adjust this range when needed
train_accuracies = []
test_accuracies = []

for n_neighbors in n_neighbors_range:
    # Create KNN model with the current number of neighbors
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=n_neighbors, weights='uniform')  # You can adjust the weights parameter as well
    
    # Wrap it with the chosen scaler from your grid search
    knn_pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('scaler', best_params_knn['scaler']), 
        ('classifier', knn)
    ])
    
    # Fit the model
    knn_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    # Calculate accuracy on training set
    y_train_pred = knn_pipeline.predict(X_train)
    train_accuracies.append(accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred))
    
    # Calculate accuracy on test set
    y_test_pred = knn_pipeline.predict(X_test)
    test_accuracies.append(accuracy_score(y_test, y_test_pred))

# Plotting the accuracies
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(n_neighbors_range, train_accuracies, label='Training Accuracy', marker='o')
plt.plot(n_neighbors_range, test_accuracies, label='Testing Accuracy', marker='o')
plt.xlabel('Number of Neighbors')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.title('KNN Accuracy vs Number of Neighbors')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

                                      max_depth=max_depth,
                                      min_samples_split=best_params_rf['classifier__min_samples_split'],
                                      min_samples_leaf=best_params_rf['classifier__min_samples_leaf'])

    # Pipeline with the current max_depth
    pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('scaler', best_params_rf['scaler']),
        ('classifier', rf_model)
    ])

    # Cross-validation for training data

    train_accuracies.append(np.mean(cv_scores))

    # Evaluating on the test data

    test_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, pipeline.predict(X_test))
    test_accuracies.append(test_accuracy)

From initial Performance of SGDClassifier in Task 1, we can see the logistic regression classifier (SGDClassifier) on the raw data yielded a good corss validation accuracy of 76.73%. This indicates a decent baseline performance, when analyzing the results from applying various classifiers to the raw time series data for subject A, we can draw several conclusions:

  • Superior Performance of Random Forest and SVM Classifiers: When evaluating alternatives, the Random Forest and SVM classifiers outperformed others with very high training accuracies (Random Forest: 98.98%, SVM: 96.60%) and excellent test accuracies (Random Forest: 95.28%, SVM: 94.49%). These models demonstrate strong learning capabilities and impressive generalization to new, unseen data.

  • Good Performance of KNN and Updated SGDClassifier: The KNN and the updated SGDClassifier also performed well, with both showing training accuracies above 92% and test accuracies above 88%. This indicates their efficacy on the dataset, with KNN achieving a notably high test accuracy of 90.55%.

  • Underperformance of Naive Bayes and Decision Tree: Naive Bayes and Decision Tree classifiers showed the lowest performance, with Naive Bayes particularly underperforming on the test set (69.29%). The Decision Tree showed signs of overfitting with a significant drop from training to test accuracy.

  • Effectiveness of Data Normalization and Classifier Selection: The improvements in accuracies across most classifiers compared to the initial SGDClassifier application suggest that data normalization and careful selection of classifiers can significantly impact performance, especially in the context of time series data.

  • General Observations: The raw time series data seems to respond well to complex models like Random Forest and SVM, indicating that the data might have complex patterns or non-linear relationships which these models can capture more effectively than simpler models.

Based on the provided accuracy results for classifiers with and without ROCKET transformation, here are some conclusions:¶

From the accuracy results, it appears that most of the classifiers, including SVM, RandomForest, and RidgeClassifier, benefit from the ROCKET transformation. However, it's essential to note that the conclusion is based solely on accuracy, and a more in-depth analysis may be required, especially considering the characteristics of time series data.

1. ROCKET transformation has positive Impact on Many Classifiers:¶

  • SVM, RidgeClassifier, and Random Forest classifier exhibit strong performance without ROCKET, achieving 96-99% accuracy on the training set and 95-98% on the testing set.

  • KNN and SGDClassifier exhibit similar performance, suggesting that they are less sensitive to the transformation.

  • The improvements seen in certain classifiers may be attributed to the ability of ROCKET to enhance the representation of time series features.

2. Understanding Time Series Data:¶

  • Feature transformations like ROCKET are designed to extract relevant information from time series sequences, making them suitable for such data. Traditional classifiers might struggle to capture some temporal dependencies from time series data.

3. Model Sensitivity and Consideration for Use Cases:¶

  • Sensitivity of models to ROCKET transformation emphasizes the importance of considering dataset characteristics.

  • Not all classifiers benefit equally, necessitating a thoughtful approach based on specific use cases.

  • It's important to consider not only accuracy but also aspects like interpretability, computational efficiency, and the nature of temporal patterns in the data.

4. Overfitting Analysis:¶

  • Without the ROCKET transformation, classifiers like SVM, RidgeClassifier, and SGDClassifier demonstrate high accuracy on the training set, indicating a potential risk of overfitting. DecisionTree and RandomForest, being more complex models, might be susceptible to overfitting, especially if there is a considerable gap between training and testing accuracies. On the other hand, NaiveBayes, with its simpler assumptions, may be less prone to overfitting.

  • With the introduction of ROCKET transformation, the impact on overfitting varies across classifiers. SVM, RandomForest, and RidgeClassifier maintain or improve performance, suggesting potential regularization effects, while DecisionTree may benefit from reduced overfitting.

5. Computational Cost:¶

  • With ROCKET transformation, there could be an additional computational cost due to the generation of random convolutional kernels. SVM and RandomForest might still have higher training times, but the transformation's efficiency could influence computational costs positively.

  • The computational expense is influenced by the number of kernels generated. As the number of kernels increases, the complexity of the transformation grows, leading to higher computational demands during both training and testing phases.

  • Optimizing the number of ROCKET kernels becomes crucial. A balance must be struck between achieving enhanced feature representation and managing computational costs effectively. Hyperparameter tuning should consider both accuracy and efficiency.

6. Variability in Results with Different Numbers of ROCKET Kernels:¶

  • Impact of Kernel Variation: Each time the ROCKET transformation is applied with a different number of kernels, it potentially alters the extracted features from the time series data. Since ROCKET generates random convolutional kernels, the feature space changes with each run, leading to variability in the model's learning and, consequently, in the accuracy results.

  • Randomness and Model Stability: The inherent randomness in the ROCKET transformation can lead to fluctuations in model performance. While one set of kernels might capture certain aspects of the time series effectively, another set might miss these aspects or capture different ones. This randomness can impact the stability and reproducibility of model training and evaluation.

My strategy involves tuning the number of ROCKET kernels by carefully balancing accuracy on both training and test sets, ensuring the model's ability to capture patterns while avoiding overfitting. This approach considers the trade-off between accuracy and computational cost, aiming for an optimal configuration that maximizes performance while maintaining efficiency.

Test to see if the main conclusions from Tasks 3 and 4 hold up with the data for subject B. Comment on your findings.

Understanding of the question:¶

Personalized Model:

A personalized model is trained on data from a single individual or subject. It's highly tailored to the specific patterns and characteristics of that individual's data. The model I applied on subject B, which is trained only on the FatigueA dataset, is an example of a personalized model. It's expected to perform well for predictions related to subject A, but may not generalize well to subject B.

Global model:

on the other hand, Global model is trained on data from multiple subjects. It aims to find patterns that are generalizable across different individuals. To create a global model, I would combine the data from both FatigueA and FatigueB (and potentially more subjects if available), and then train the model on this combined dataset.

The results from applying global models trained on Subject A's data to Subject B's data yield some interesting insights:¶

Performance of Non-ROCKET Models:¶

  • The non-ROCKET models, especially the SVM classifier, show a significant drop in accuracy when tested on Subject B's data. This indicates that the model, while highly effective for Subject A's data, does not generalize well to different subjects.

  • The Random Forest classifier, although perfect on the training data (overfitting), has a low accuracy on Subject B's test data, indicating poor generalizability.

  • The SGD classifier performs relatively better than the SVM and Random Forest classifiers in terms of generalization.

Performance of ROCKET-Transformed Models:¶

  • The ROCKET-transformed models show remarkably better performance on Subject B's data. This suggests that the ROCKET transformation is effective in extracting relevant, generalizable features from time-series data.

  • The SVM with ROCKET transformation performs exceptionally well, indicating its robustness and ability to generalize across different subjects.

  • The Random Forest and SGD classifiers with ROCKET also show improved generalization compared to their non-ROCKET counterparts.

Conclusion:¶

  • ROCKET transformation greatly improves model generalizability across different subjects. It's likely due to its ability to extract important, universal features from time-series data.

  • Non-ROCKET models, like Random Forest, can overfit the training data, leading to poor performance on new, unseen data.

  • In time-series data involving various subjects, using transformations like ROCKET can be more beneficial. SVM and SGD classifiers demonstrate superior adaptability.

Impact of ROCKET Transformation:¶

Personalized Model Superiority:¶

  • The personalized model (model created by subject B) shows better performance compared to the global model (model trained on subject A then applied on subject B). This suggests that models tailored to individual subjects (personalized models) are more effective, likely due to being more closely aligned with the specific characteristics and data of the individual subject.

Best Performing Model:¶

  • The best performing model is the personalized model with ROCKET, achieving an accuracy of 97.57%. This indicates that the combination of personalized modeling and ROCKET transformation yields the most favorable results.

ROCKET's Role in Overcoming Generalization Issues:¶

  • Although the global model is less accurate than the personalized model, the significant improvement with ROCKET suggests that this transformation helps in mitigating some of the generalization issues, making the global model more adaptable to different subjects.

Conclusion:¶

  • These results indicate that both subject A and B benefit from the effectiveness of ROCKET transformations, which improved their model accuracy and that the personalized model outperforms the global model in this particular application.
